Fairly terrifying. I hope those last flake crimps never rip...

Shoutout Will and Joaquin for sussing all the beta. Only reason I was able to flash.
I can’t stop splitting tips, but at least I can still throw down some old projects. Stoked.

Four days on it, 2 micro beta additions in me, and immeasurable hope. 

Fell after sticking the good crimp a half dozen times, was starting to wonder if I wasn’t going to be able to finish it this trip. So. Freaking. Stoked.
It’s too bad you have to fight so hard not to dab, otherwise this climb would be all time.

3 days of effort. Started sitting with the lowest two pockets, a three finger stack for the left and a small two finger pocket for the right. Not exactly sure if that’s the actual start but didn’t want to start to high. Amazing line, if only that tree wasn’t there.
Smol boulder, big fun.
Swapped the start hold hands and got a high left toe in the smile. Made it feel leagues easier than the normal way which seems impossible to me. Such a surprising start to my last day!
3 days, hero sending on the last day of the trip was friggin rad.

No idea how I held on long enough to top this, pretty sure my hands were numb from move three onwards. 

Also can't wait to see how long it takes Jenn to notice I called this soft.
Hard to believe it, but the dab potential is pretty low on this one.
Real rage send on this one. So glad I didn't fall and get penetrated by the bush.
In classic me fashion, just had to punt once in order to send.
Always looked at this as a crimp testpiece, can’t believe I finally finished it. Psyched.
Pumped out of my god damn mind, somehow stayed on. Last climb of the decade, who knows what’s in store for next year.
My head game needs work. I also need to get better at topping out marginally scary boulders.
Yay tall person beta.
When the group doesn't want to hike out in the dark, you try real hard to flash. And sometimes it works. Neat.
This climb is bad and you should feel bad. 3 stars? The fuck?
Red springs is a terrible area.
I've never tried so hard to send v5. So I'm upgrading. Fight me IRL. Good climb though.
Super interesting movement. V fun. So happy to be back in Bishy.
To loosely quote the great boulder philosopher Nathanbro: “If the climbs goes, then it must be soft”. Also tendonitis is a bitch, feels like my left arm is going to fall off.

What can I say, when the studly Davey/Nate duo are around, and I see that sweet sweet kneebar potential, the pants have just GOT to come off. 

Climbs well, looks swell, and has got a sweet-as kneebar for rell. 3 stars, would recommend.

Pretty much tried this thing once a year for the last 5 years to no avail, so I was very convinced that I would take hard for the grade if/when I did it. And then it went first try this trip with a tinge of tendonitis so... it's soft. I should have known.
More impressive than the climb was that I somehow got Kody psyched to try this. Which says more about the impressiveness of this climb.

Crimping is so 2019. 2020 is the year of the finger locks. 

Between this, Hard Crack, and the thoroughly mediocre Wet Dream, I think I might be developing a taste for... crack climbing? Sign me up to be a trad daddy and tell me where I can pick up my dad bod.
Felt harder than 9 to me. Sweet as fall in toe hook when I hit the right hand undercling. Also Natebro is losing his mind, I haven’t been to Every Color in 5ever.
Being a little tall helps for the crux. Dope movement, can't believe I like a trav so much.
Can’t believe I’ve never done this thing before, and how good it is. So sick.
-1 star for all the rat poop in the jug on top. Otherwise pretty sweet.

#flexonem #wegothimboys #ohisthatyourboochoosle?causeithinkigotit
Pretty strange, pretty fun. Trip duuuuuuuubbb.
Nice day of sending to combat the messiness of life.

This is why I climb.
Someone's going to die topping this thing out someday. Some of those holds are grade-a certified choss.
Had to pull on and do the crux once just to get the #softsecondgo. Cool though.

Can’t imagine a better way to end my funemployment trip. Something like 5 days of work, punted HARD on day 4 and couldn’t repeat the beginning, but managed to pull the send out of my boochoosle today. Not sure what the future holds but psyched to see what’s in store.

All the stars. Rad.

Neat.

Derrick's beta was clutch. Feels less scary than it looks.
Coming for the sitter.
Can't believe it took me until now to do this. Really good.
The key to sending is being completely wrecked from digging the van out of a snow bank the night before.
Really great line, more enjoyable than Ill Cave for me.
The difficulty and enjoyment of this boulder is entirely dependent on how the hand jam/slot feels to you. Really wish it was a different hold, detracted from an otherwise amazing line in my opinion.
My skin is hot gahbage. Now time to add one move for all the points.
What a heroic throw.
Coulda sent in a session, and then it ended up taking three more. Solo night sesh, hope the bears liked my music.
Turned into an epic. That last move is hard for me. Shoutout the Sandbox for a much needed, super fun weekend. Ya'll the realest.

It was hotter than two rats fucking in a wool sock, still managed to pull out the send. Good climb, fun day, and came up with 'Robinhood and his Merry Men'-ing someone, which just turned out to be all time.

Had an out of body experience where I got up to the last third of the climb and all I could think about was that I didn't really want to do this boulder. Body kept doing moves though, and then I was on top. One of the strangest experiences I've had. Life is weird these days...
Didn't expect to get on this, definitely didn't expect to send. Chalk another send up to the #sbdiet. Also shoutout Chris Hoss for not downgrading, I really needed that confidence to log this.

I don't know if it was the four sessions it took to do Party Animal, I don't know if it was the temps, but DAMN this felt easy. Had to hop on Friday night to get those sending temps and they did not disappoint.

Even better than than Wolfpack. Low end for the grade, maybe only v11, but as you get older and more wise you realize Jens don’t know shit and you should always take the grade.

First ever trip outdoors was a day trip to this, I'd been climbing for maybe a couple months and saw this and knew I wanted to do it someday. Cool feeling to come back to it all these years later and have it feel pretty casual.
Two mover, topout was the best part.
I remembered the topout being intimidating, but with the confidence that only comes with a bunch of strong boys below you, I pulled my big kids pants up high and realized this was soft.

The boulder itself is amazing, and this was such a good way to end the weekend.

Maybe I’m more fit right now than I thought…

Used to be terrible at underclings, but after multiple days of wrist curls, I'm now just bad at them. Hell yea. Why anyone goes right hand first is beyond me.

Went to Black Sea to support the crew and saw chalk to the left, a nice new landing built, and the sweetest grips this side of the Mississippi. Apparently David knows the fine young men who built the landing the night before, and told us they were working on the FA, but to be honest David talks a lot, and I don't always listen. 
Managed to climb straight up from the start jug via a big first deadpoint and turns out it's pretty fun. Only after we got home did I find out that this Albino accidentally snaked the FA... Oops. 
But the story doesn't end there, dear reader, because never one to be outdone, Davey wanted to climb it too to "help confirm the grade" (aka call me a weak little reptile), but after a hour of trying the Grecian God himself couldn't even do the first move! So I told him if he could repeat Black Sea in a try or two, I'd call it v9 instead of v8 to assuage his ego. And boy oh boy, I've never seen this man try harder in his life. Since he retro flashed the B Sea, I'm giving this v9.
Big shoutouts to Jed and Ben for building the landing, chalking the holds, and being kind enough to let me snake the FA. That was very kind of you fine folks.
